course_introduction:
LAWS7023 Business and Corporate Law is an introduction to the legal rules regulating business in Australia today, and to the use of those legal rules to solve simple legal problems. You will learn about the Australian legal system; the rules regulating the causing of harm, the making and enforcement of deals, dealing with consumers and competitors, and the protection of IP; and the rules associated with corporate and partnership regulation, including the nature of companies and company law; the corporate form; corporate governance; directors' duties; shareholders' rights; corporate finance; corporate liability; corporate takeovers; external administration; liquidation; and partnerships. Your final grade will be based upon your level of understanding of and participation in the course, determined by reference to various assessment items including:

Two submissions on ILAC problem questions;

An ILAC assignment;

A mid-semester short answer question and multiple-choice question exam;

Two in-class multiple choice question exams;

And a Final Short Answer and ILAC problem question exam.

Course Changes in Response to Previous Student Feedback

The assessment has been changed in order to better develop students' ability to solve legal problems scenarios using ILAC technique - Issue, Law, Application and Conclusion - and to better prepare students for the assignment and the final examination.

other_learning_activities_information:
Seminars

Seminars are a forum where, within an analytical framework offered by the lecturer, students and lecturer can:

Explore theoretical and legal concepts relevant to the topic;

Critically evaluate these concepts and explore their relationships to one another;

Identify the central conceptual, intellectual and doctrinal questions raised by the material under consideration;

Place the material discussed into a wider intellectual and practical context.

Seminars also offer students an interactive forum within which to explore in greater detail and depth the issues introduced by the lecturer and to engage with the lecturer and other students in exploring those issues.

Seminars afford students an opportunity to develop their skills in analytical reasoning and argument. As an interactive learning forum, the seminar is dependent upon all students having prepared the material to be considered and being prepared to engage in debate.

In a negative sense, seminars are not for:

Delivering an exclusive and exhaustive account of the material that the student needs to learn;

Reading material that students can read for themselves.

